{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17085"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.04,0.71,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70076"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55539"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5119"},{"type":"tags","id":"8498"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23522"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70076"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETestosterone is the primary male sex hormone responsible for the development and maintenance of male sexual characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the primary site of testosterone synthesis in men?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal cortex","Prostate gland","Seminiferous tubules","Leydig cells of testes","Sertoli cells of testes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ELeydig cells of the testes\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary site of testosterone synthesis in men, producing approximately 95% of circulating testosterone. These specialised cells contain the necessary enzymes to convert cholesterol into testosterone through a series of biochemical steps.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E produces small amounts of androgens but is not the primary source of testosterone.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate gland\u003C/strong\u003E is a target organ for testosterone action but does not synthesise testosterone.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eseminiferous tubules\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in sperm production but not testosterone synthesis.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ESertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E support sperm development but do not produce significant amounts of testosterone.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003ETestosterone production is regulated by luteinising hormone from the anterior pituitary gland. In target tissues, testosterone can be converted to dihydrotestosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha reductase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testosterone is primarily synthesised from cholesterol in the Leydig cells of the testes.","The hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis regulates testosterone production through luteinising hormone.","Testosterone is converted to dihydrotestosterone in target tissues by 5-alpha reductase."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","